                          </div>
                          <p
                            id="fs-idm63696"
                          >So, you can use food labels to count your Calories. But where do the values come from? And how accurate are they? The caloric content of foods can be determined by using bomb calorimetry; that is, by burning the food and measuring the energy it contains. A sample of food is weighed, mixed in a blender, freeze-dried, ground into powder, and formed into a pellet. The pellet is burned inside a bomb calorimeter, and the measured temperature change is converted into energy per gram of food.</p>
                          <p id="fs-idm53626320">
                            Today, the caloric content on food labels is derived using a method called the
                            <span
                              class="no-emphasis"
                              data-type="term"
                              group-by="A"
                              id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                            >Atwater system</span> that uses the average caloric content of the different chemical constituents of food, protein, carbohydrate, and fats. The average amounts are those given in the equation and are derived from the various results given by bomb calorimetry of whole foods. The carbohydrate amount is discounted a certain amount for the fiber content, which is indigestible carbohydrate. To determine the energy content of a food, the quantities of carbohydrate, protein, and fat are each multiplied by the average Calories per gram for each and the products summed to obtain the total energy.
                          </p>
                        </div>
                      </div>

                      <div
                        class="chemistry link-to-learning"
                        data-type="note"
                        id="fs-idm72852528"
                      >
                        <h3 class="os-title" data-type="title">
                          <span class="os-title-label">Link to Learning</span>
                        </h3>
                        <div class="os-note-body">
                          <p id="fs-idm56857472">
                            Click on this
                            <a
                              href="http://openstaxcollege.org/l/16USDA"
                              rel="noopener nofollow"
                              target="_blank"
                            >link</a> to access the US Department of Agriculture (USDA) National Nutrient Database, containing nutritional information on over 8000 foods.
                          </p>
                        </div>
                      </div>

